docs.abstract: The grocery-store industry now faces, in addition to overseas competitors, a deep-pocketed rival with a track record of moving customers online.

docs.abstract: Amazon Wardrobe, part of the Prime service and part of the company’s effort to expand in apparel, will let customers order three to 15 items of clothing without buying it.
docs.snippet: Amazon Wardrobe, part of the Prime service and part of the company’s effort to expand in apparel, will let customers order three to 15 items of clothing without buying it.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — For many people, buying clothing online is not worth the hassle of getting a pair of pants or a shirt that does not fit. Many retailers have sought to eliminate that risk by offering free returns on clothing, but now Amazon is going even further.

headline.main: Amazon Will Let Customers Try On Clothes Before Buying
headline.print_headline: Amazon Apparel Plan: Try Before You Buy, Send Back the Rest

docs.abstract: With its purchase of Whole Foods, Amazon is buying access to a large pool of wealthy customers.
docs.snippet: With its purchase of Whole Foods, Amazon is buying access to a large pool of wealthy customers.
docs.lead_paragraph: Amazon.com just bought its way to the top of the food chain. The e-commerce giant is going whole hog for United States grocery stores with the $13.7 billion acquisition of the upscale chain Whole Foods Market.

docs.abstract: A tweet may have implied support for legislation helping states force online retailers to collect sales taxes. But that is already Amazon’s practice.
docs.snippet: A tweet may have implied support for legislation helping states force online retailers to collect sales taxes. But that is already Amazon’s practice.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Trump may not have meant to, but on Wednesday he seemed to endorse a longer reach for the tax collector.

headline.main: Trump, Amazon and ‘Internet Taxes’: What Did He Mean?

docs.abstract: The battle to sell men’s shirts and food, and just about everything else, is a competition that will define the future of retail.
docs.snippet: The battle to sell men’s shirts and food, and just about everything else, is a competition that will define the future of retail.
docs.lead_paragraph: With Amazon buying the high-end grocery chain Whole Foods, something retail analysts have known for years is now apparent to everyone: The online retailer is on a collision course with Walmart to try to be the predominant seller of pretty much everything you buy.

headline.main: The Amazon-Walmart Showdown That Explains the Modern Economy
headline.print_headline: Behemoths  In a Battle  To Sell You  Everything

docs.abstract: Timothy Cook, Jeff Bezos and Eric Schmidt were among 18 tech executives at a forum held by an administration they have had conflicts with.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Silicon Valley is fuming about President Trump’s stance on climate and immigration, but top technology executives still made a pilgrimage to the White House on Monday to discuss a potential upgrade of government technology.

headline.main: Tech Titans Make Pilgrimage to White House to Discuss Government Systems
headline.print_headline: Silicon Valley Chiefs Attend White House Forum on Government Tech
